WEBVTT

00:50.184 --> 00:51.419
[Man]
She said,

00:51.419 --> 00:54.188
"Do you think it'd be fun
if we got married?"

00:54.188 --> 00:55.823
[Woman]
And what did you say?

00:55.823 --> 00:58.125
[Man]
I took her up on it.

00:58.125 --> 01:01.095
I never wanted to be
away from her.

01:01.095 --> 01:03.130
She had the spark of life.

01:03.130 --> 01:05.633
[no audible dialogue]

02:28.482 --> 02:30.150
Careful.

02:33.153 --> 02:35.489
When did we last
wash that sweater?

02:37.491 --> 02:38.859
Right after the war.

02:38.859 --> 02:41.395
[chuckling]

02:44.632 --> 02:45.533
Christmas.

02:45.533 --> 02:47.368
In the '50s sometime
or the '60s.

02:47.368 --> 02:48.536
[laughing]
Shut up.

03:20.267 --> 03:21.635
I'll go make the fire.

03:58.238 --> 04:00.507
"You climbed
the bank and said,

04:00.507 --> 04:03.611
"'This is how you touch
other women,

04:03.611 --> 04:07.948
"the grass cutter's wife,
the lime burner's daughter.

04:07.948 --> 04:09.350
"And you searched your arms

04:09.350 --> 04:11.418
for the missing perfume
and knew--"

04:11.418 --> 04:14.254
Don't worry, darling.

04:14.254 --> 04:16.457
I expect I'm just
losing my mind.

04:16.457 --> 04:18.892
Shh-shh.

04:18.892 --> 04:22.329
"What good is it to be
the lime burner's daughter,

04:22.329 --> 04:24.365
"left with no trace

04:24.365 --> 04:26.934
"as if not spoken to
in the act of love,

04:26.934 --> 04:30.571
"as if wounded without
the pleasure of a scar.

04:30.571 --> 04:34.608
"You touched your belly
to my hands in the dry air

04:34.608 --> 04:39.546
"and said, 'I am
the cinnamon peeler's wife.

04:39.546 --> 04:41.615
Smell me.'"

05:45.612 --> 05:49.683
When I look away,
I forget what yellow means.

05:49.683 --> 05:52.453
But I can look again.

05:52.453 --> 05:56.590
Sometimes there's something
delicious in oblivion.

05:56.590 --> 05:58.926
I think you're
supposed to be able

05:58.926 --> 06:02.596
to put your fingers
inside the curled petal

06:02.596 --> 06:05.466
and feel the heat.

06:05.466 --> 06:07.468
[Man]
Well?

06:09.937 --> 06:12.606
I can't be sure.

06:12.606 --> 06:15.609
I can't be sure
if what I can feel

06:15.609 --> 06:19.079
is the heat
or my imagination.

06:20.881 --> 06:22.950
The heat attracts the bugs.

06:24.818 --> 06:28.589
Nature never fools around
just being decorative.

06:38.866 --> 06:41.535
[car beeping]

06:56.850 --> 06:58.752
[knocking]

07:04.124 --> 07:05.859
Yes?

07:05.859 --> 07:08.095
I don't quite know
how to introduce myself.

07:08.095 --> 07:11.899
I used to see your husband
at Meadowlake.

07:11.899 --> 07:14.001
I'm a regular visitor
there myself.

07:19.139 --> 07:20.874
Those are lovely flowers.

07:22.709 --> 07:26.113
I've never seen
those purple ones before.

07:26.113 --> 07:27.881
Hmm.

07:27.881 --> 07:30.150
The earth there must
really appeal to them.

07:35.222 --> 07:36.757
[chuckling]

07:36.757 --> 07:37.691
What?

07:37.691 --> 07:39.993
You could just
open the drawers.

07:39.993 --> 07:41.128
Remind yourself.

07:41.128 --> 07:42.596
What?

07:42.596 --> 07:43.931
Maybe
all the labels and lists

07:43.931 --> 07:45.566
are defeating the purpose.

07:47.801 --> 07:49.536
If you stopped
thinking about things

07:49.536 --> 07:50.804
the moment
you write them down,

07:50.804 --> 07:55.742
maybe that's the end
of your need to recall.

07:55.742 --> 07:57.978
I heard a story
at a dinner party

07:57.978 --> 08:00.047
about the German soldiers
on border patrol

08:00.047 --> 08:03.550
in Czechoslovakia
during the war.

08:03.550 --> 08:05.652
I heard it from that
Czech student of yours.

08:05.652 --> 08:07.187
Veronica.

08:07.187 --> 08:10.624
We spoke once
at a dinner party.

08:10.624 --> 08:12.626
Don't be nervous.

08:12.626 --> 08:15.028
It's a good story.

08:15.028 --> 08:19.766
She told me that each
of the German patrol dogs

08:19.766 --> 08:23.704
wore a sign saying "hund."

08:23.704 --> 08:25.806
"Why?" said the Czechs.

08:25.806 --> 08:31.144
And the Germans replied,
"Because that is a hund."

08:50.831 --> 08:52.299
It was one
of those craft shows

08:52.299 --> 08:55.636
where you look around
and wonder that the laws
of supply and demand

08:55.636 --> 08:58.772
can allow for the production
of so many macramÃ© ducks.

08:58.772 --> 09:00.207
[laughs]
Oh, God, those things
are everywhere.

09:00.207 --> 09:03.277
What do you do with them?
Oh, come on, Phoebe,
you've got one of those.

09:03.277 --> 09:05.212
You use it as a--
what do you call it--

09:05.212 --> 09:06.747
a light fixture holder
or som--

09:06.747 --> 09:08.081
I do not.
Phoebe, in the...

09:08.081 --> 09:09.616
Oh, yes.
Wait a second, I do.

09:09.616 --> 09:11.685
Fiona gave it to me.

09:11.685 --> 09:13.820
Yes, I did.
[chuckling]

09:14.922 --> 09:16.690
Would anybody
like some more?

09:16.690 --> 09:18.091
Mm.

09:28.902 --> 09:31.004
Ween...

09:36.176 --> 09:39.980
Wai-- Wain--

09:39.980 --> 09:42.149
No, but I'll have
a touch of wine.

09:42.149 --> 09:43.750
Yeah, Fiona,
that would be lovely.

09:43.750 --> 09:45.152
Some more wain.

09:49.122 --> 09:50.824
The thing is...

09:53.226 --> 09:55.896
half the time
I wander around

09:55.896 --> 09:57.664
looking for something
which I know

09:57.664 --> 10:00.801
is very pertinent.

10:00.801 --> 10:03.837
I can't remember what it is.

10:05.772 --> 10:10.377
Once the idea is gone,
everything is gone.

10:11.778 --> 10:14.081
I just wander around

10:14.081 --> 10:15.983
trying to figure out
what it was

10:15.983 --> 10:18.685
that was so important
earlier.

10:22.189 --> 10:25.926
I think I may be
beginning to disappear.

10:33.967 --> 10:36.103
[Woman]
And what year is it?

10:36.103 --> 10:37.838
2003.

10:37.838 --> 10:40.941
Fiona, if you found
a letter on the street,

10:40.941 --> 10:43.377
addressed,
with a stamp on it,

10:43.377 --> 10:45.645
what would you do with it?

10:45.645 --> 10:46.913
I'd mail it.

10:46.913 --> 10:48.849
And where would
you put it to mail it?

11:00.394 --> 11:03.864
And if there was a fire
in a movie theater,

11:03.864 --> 11:07.868
and you were the first person
to spot that fire,

11:07.868 --> 11:09.336
what would you do?

11:12.873 --> 11:14.808
Well, we don't go
to the movies much anymore,

11:14.808 --> 11:16.676
do we, Grant?

11:16.676 --> 11:20.047
All those multiplexes showing
the same American garbage.

11:32.959 --> 11:34.928
Have you seen my coat?

11:34.928 --> 11:36.963
There it is, dear.

11:36.963 --> 11:38.065
It's on your chair.

11:40.200 --> 11:41.168
Oh, yes.

11:41.168 --> 11:42.235
Fiona, would you mind

11:42.235 --> 11:44.838
if I asked you
a few more questions?

11:44.838 --> 11:47.340
Would you mind
taking a seat?

11:49.709 --> 11:53.046
I was just feeling
a little cold, that's all.

11:55.849 --> 11:58.985
[baby burbling]

12:03.290 --> 12:05.926
[sotto voce]
What an ugly baby.

12:23.043 --> 12:25.412
When did we move
into this cottage?

12:25.412 --> 12:29.082
Was it last year
or the year before?

12:34.855 --> 12:36.189
[sigh]

12:38.325 --> 12:40.193
No.
It was longer than that.

12:40.193 --> 12:43.330
It was when I left
the university,

12:43.330 --> 12:44.531
20 years ago.

12:49.870 --> 12:51.404
Hmm.

12:51.404 --> 12:54.341
Well, that's shocking.

12:57.310 --> 12:59.212
[chuckle]

13:06.920 --> 13:10.423
Let's just see how it goes,
shall we, hmm?

13:11.925 --> 13:12.959
Hmm?

13:12.959 --> 13:15.996
[Grant]
How is your husband doing?

13:15.996 --> 13:17.464
Okay.

13:17.464 --> 13:20.066
He and my wife struck up
quite a close friendship.

13:21.535 --> 13:23.069
I heard about that.

13:24.971 --> 13:26.940
So, uh,

13:26.940 --> 13:29.409
I'd like to speak to you
about something.

13:31.178 --> 13:33.547
If you have a minute.

13:33.547 --> 13:36.316
My husband did not
try to start anything
with your wife,

13:36.316 --> 13:38.084
if that's what
you're getting at.

13:38.084 --> 13:39.920
He did not
try to molest her.

13:39.920 --> 13:41.154
He's incapable of it.

13:41.154 --> 13:42.889
And anyway, he wouldn't.

13:42.889 --> 13:45.992
From what I hear,
it was the other way
around.

13:45.992 --> 13:47.961
No, uh,
that isn't it at all.

13:47.961 --> 13:51.164
I didn't come here
with any complaints.

13:51.164 --> 13:53.433
Oh.

13:53.433 --> 13:55.569
Oh, well, I'm sorry.
I thought you did.

13:59.940 --> 14:01.107
Maybe you should come in.

14:01.107 --> 14:05.111
It's not as warm a day
as it looks.

14:09.616 --> 14:12.185
[Fiona]
"Never let a person
make you feel guilty

14:12.185 --> 14:13.987
for your anger with God."

14:15.088 --> 14:18.024
Hmm. Random.

14:20.427 --> 14:24.231
I can't even see
what the point is.

14:24.231 --> 14:27.300
We can't be certain
this is what--

14:27.300 --> 14:28.501
You're far too young.

14:28.501 --> 14:30.370
"Should the patient
afflicted with the disease

14:30.370 --> 14:33.206
"remain at home...

14:33.206 --> 14:36.943
the caregiver
will very often
be the spouse."

14:38.545 --> 14:41.081
"The caregiver must preside
over the degeneration

14:41.081 --> 14:43.883
"of someone he or she
loves very much,

14:43.883 --> 14:45.552
"must do this
for years and years

14:45.552 --> 14:48.288
"with the news always
getting worse, not better,

14:48.288 --> 14:50.090
"must put up sometimes
with deranged

14:50.090 --> 14:53.159
"but at the same time
very personal insults,

14:53.159 --> 14:55.629
"and must somehow learn
to smile through it all.

14:55.629 --> 14:57.364
"Caregivers must
be able to diagnose

14:57.364 --> 14:59.633
"a wide variety
of ordinary ailments

14:59.633 --> 15:01.635
"under extraordinary
circumstances.

15:01.635 --> 15:04.037
"Imagine the person
you love the most

15:04.037 --> 15:05.605
"suddenly upset
about something,

15:05.605 --> 15:08.174
"but completely unable
to communicate the problem

15:08.174 --> 15:11.111
or even to understand it
himself."

15:14.214 --> 15:16.082
Sounds like a regular marriage.

15:16.082 --> 15:17.317
[chuckle]

16:20.347 --> 16:22.315
[sigh]

17:54.741 --> 17:56.242
Hello, there!

17:59.579 --> 18:01.347
[shivering]
Oh!

18:01.347 --> 18:03.383
Hello, there.

18:50.563 --> 18:53.366
We are at that stage,
Grant.

18:56.369 --> 18:58.538
We are at that stage.

19:04.410 --> 19:05.879
[sigh]

19:08.581 --> 19:10.350
Well...

19:13.520 --> 19:15.688
if we do think of it...

19:15.688 --> 19:18.892
if we do...

19:18.892 --> 19:23.830
then it must be as something
that isn't permanent.

19:25.798 --> 19:30.670
A kind of experimental
treatment or...

19:32.505 --> 19:35.842
a rest cure of sorts.

19:46.719 --> 19:49.756
All right.

19:49.756 --> 19:50.857
All right.

19:50.857 --> 19:53.426
We can think
of it that way.

19:56.763 --> 20:00.466
We have to sit in the kitchen,
where I can hear Aubrey.

20:07.473 --> 20:10.510
Well, you might as well
have a cup of coffee.

20:10.510 --> 20:12.545
Thank you.

20:12.545 --> 20:18.351
My son put him on
the Sports Channel
a year ago Christmas.

20:18.351 --> 20:20.486
I don't know what
we'd do without it.

20:20.486 --> 20:22.488
Must be a struggle.

20:23.790 --> 20:25.892
Well, you know.

20:25.892 --> 20:28.628
You know what
struggle is by now.

20:31.497 --> 20:33.700
You're sure?
I'm sure.

20:35.635 --> 20:39.405
You don't want
to just get a sense
of the place?

20:39.405 --> 20:41.808
I don't want to make
this decision alone.

20:45.845 --> 20:46.946
What place?

20:51.517 --> 20:52.652
Just kidding!

20:54.420 --> 20:55.622
Fuck off.

21:03.696 --> 21:07.734
You're not making
this decision alone, Grant.

21:07.734 --> 21:10.436
I've already
made up my mind.

21:15.675 --> 21:16.576
Okay.

21:46.372 --> 21:48.374
[Woman]
It's time to go home now.

21:48.374 --> 21:50.009
[Man]
No, no.
Mrs. Taylor--

21:50.009 --> 21:51.844
Hi. Is this your son?
Yeah. I'm her son.

21:51.844 --> 21:55.048
Hi. I'm Betty.
It's time for your bath.

21:55.048 --> 21:57.083
Bath.
Yeah.

21:57.083 --> 21:58.785
You have to have
a bath now.

21:58.785 --> 22:00.553
Mama.

22:00.553 --> 22:03.756
Mr. Andersson?
Madeleine Montpelier.

22:03.756 --> 22:05.692
I'm the supervisor
here at Meadowlake.
Hi, there.

22:05.692 --> 22:08.528
I'm just going to take
you on the quick tour
of the facility,

22:08.528 --> 22:09.929
and then we can sit down

22:09.929 --> 22:11.464
and discuss
Mrs. Andersson's condition

22:11.464 --> 22:13.966
and the appropriate time
for admitting her.

22:17.437 --> 22:19.439
As you can see, we get
a lot of natural light.

22:19.439 --> 22:22.075
Yes,
I can see that.

22:22.075 --> 22:23.810
This
is my favorite room.

22:23.810 --> 22:25.645
Look, over there,
as you can see,

22:25.645 --> 22:27.680
they have
a puzzle on the go.

22:27.680 --> 22:28.848
They always have
a puzzle on the go.

22:28.848 --> 22:31.484
This works.
You know, it's real
important to us here

22:31.484 --> 22:33.720
that our residents
maintain social function,

22:33.720 --> 22:36.489
so a lot of our activities
and our whole layout

22:36.489 --> 22:37.457
is really geared toward--

22:37.457 --> 22:39.092
Hello, there,
Miss Madeleine.

22:39.092 --> 22:41.027
Hello, Michael.

22:41.027 --> 22:42.995
Now, as you can see,
we're coming into
our common room,

22:42.995 --> 22:45.998
and again, we're really
emphasizing everybody
being social.

22:45.998 --> 22:47.533
So you can
bring the family.

22:47.533 --> 22:48.735
Everybody
can come and visit.

22:48.735 --> 22:51.471
We have
a state-of-the-art
entertainment system

22:51.471 --> 22:53.740
so the residents
can gather
and watch together.

22:53.740 --> 22:55.575
Hi, Madeleine.
Hello, ladies.

22:55.575 --> 22:57.610
Hello, Madeleine.
I got a Christmas sweater.

22:57.610 --> 22:59.579
Aren't you festive!

22:59.579 --> 23:01.114
And this
is our quiet corner

23:01.114 --> 23:04.150
for crafts and reading
and reflection.

23:04.150 --> 23:07.854
We have a lot of activities
for physical activity.

23:07.854 --> 23:11.057
Balloon badminton
and sit and fit.

23:11.057 --> 23:14.560
And here we have our
lovely new dining room.

23:14.560 --> 23:18.064
We can accommodate
any dietary preferences
or restrictions.

23:18.064 --> 23:22.068
We're just serving up
a little Christmas dinner
early for the families.

23:22.068 --> 23:24.036
The old Meadowlake
is just next door,

23:24.036 --> 23:27.406
and that's a day center
now, but, um...

23:27.406 --> 23:29.142
this for the permanent
residents.

23:29.142 --> 23:30.643
This is
brand-spanking new.

23:30.643 --> 23:32.612
So let's go upstairs,
shall we?

23:34.947 --> 23:37.717
Just taking my tea
for a ride.

23:38.584 --> 23:41.654
Oh, look at this one,
Flo.

23:41.654 --> 23:44.157
He's a real charmer,
isn't he?

23:44.157 --> 23:46.893
Would you say,
are you a charmer?

23:46.893 --> 23:49.162
I think you could say
I was kind of a charmer.

23:49.162 --> 23:51.731
[chuckles]
You're a rascal.

23:51.731 --> 23:53.866
Mr. Andersson is here
about his wife, Eliza.
Behave yourself.

23:53.866 --> 23:56.169
Ahh.
I should have known it.

23:56.169 --> 23:58.871
At this age, it's--

24:00.139 --> 24:02.809
What do the kids
call it, Flo? It's--

24:02.809 --> 24:04.877
It's a real clusterfuck.

24:04.877 --> 24:07.079
All the charmers are taken.

24:07.079 --> 24:09.882
Or dead. Mostly dead.
[elevator dings]

24:09.882 --> 24:11.884
You're kind of charming
yourself, sweetheart.

24:13.219 --> 24:14.220
Shall we?

24:23.062 --> 24:25.531
This is our second floor,
the extended care wing.

24:25.531 --> 24:26.899
The elevators, of course,

24:26.899 --> 24:28.034
have the lockdown system,

24:28.034 --> 24:30.469
and this is where
the patients can move to

24:30.469 --> 24:32.572
once they become
more progressed.

24:32.572 --> 24:35.241
Interesting choice
of words.

24:35.241 --> 24:38.544
Why don't I show you
some of the rooms here,
while we're at it?

24:38.544 --> 24:40.847
Then we can go back down
and see the regular rooms

24:40.847 --> 24:41.914
where Mrs. Andersson
will be living.

24:41.914 --> 24:44.550
No, that will not
be necessary.

24:44.550 --> 24:46.752
My wife will not be
progressing to this floor.

24:46.752 --> 24:48.988
All right.

24:48.988 --> 24:50.656
â™ª [Muzak]

24:50.656 --> 24:51.958
Who chooses the music?

24:51.958 --> 24:53.726
I'm sorry?

24:53.726 --> 24:54.961
I'm assuming
it's not the residents.

24:54.961 --> 24:58.231
I don't see any of them
singing along.

24:58.231 --> 25:02.034
Yeah, well. You know the rooms
on the regular floors all have
their own stereo systems

25:02.034 --> 25:04.203
so the patients can listen
to whatever they like.

25:04.203 --> 25:05.171
How kind.

25:07.173 --> 25:10.743
Now, we don't admit anyone
during the month of December,

25:10.743 --> 25:12.678
so Mrs. Andersson will
have to wait till January

25:12.678 --> 25:14.714
to make the big move.

25:14.714 --> 25:19.285
Just December, Christmas,
you know, too many
emotional pitfalls.

25:19.285 --> 25:21.153
Right.
Sorry to interrupt,
Madeleine.

25:21.153 --> 25:22.855
I'm looking for
those documents
on Aubrey Burke.

25:22.855 --> 25:24.757
Sure. Go ahead.

25:24.757 --> 25:27.760
Mr. Andersson,
this is Kristy,
our new managing nurse.

25:27.760 --> 25:30.029
Against some people's
better judgment.

25:30.029 --> 25:32.031
Now, now.
[chuckles]

25:32.031 --> 25:34.300
Mr. Andersson is here
about his wife,
Mrs. Andersson,

25:34.300 --> 25:35.768
who will be
joining us in January.

25:35.768 --> 25:36.903
Hi, there.
Hi.

25:36.903 --> 25:38.037
We also have a policy,

25:38.037 --> 25:39.805
which I'm sure you saw
in the brochure,

25:39.805 --> 25:41.807
that our new residents
are not allowed visitors

25:41.807 --> 25:43.743
or receiving phone calls
during the first 30 days,

25:43.743 --> 25:45.711
just to give them
a chance to settle in.

25:45.711 --> 25:46.946
What sort of visitors?

25:50.983 --> 25:53.853
Everyone.
Even close relatives.

25:53.853 --> 25:55.554
I couldn't just
leave her here.

25:55.554 --> 25:57.957
We understand,
it is very difficult

25:57.957 --> 26:00.693
to leave a loved one
in a new environment
for so long,

26:00.693 --> 26:03.829
but most people need
that time to settle in.

26:03.829 --> 26:05.765
Before we had
this rule in place,

26:05.765 --> 26:07.733
residents would forget
again and again

26:07.733 --> 26:08.968
why they were being
left here.

26:08.968 --> 26:10.169
Whereas we find,

26:10.169 --> 26:12.872
you give them the month
to settle in,

26:12.872 --> 26:15.174
and they're happy as clams.

26:15.174 --> 26:18.978
And after that,
a little visit home
every now and then,

26:18.978 --> 26:20.947
perfectly fine.

26:20.947 --> 26:22.782
We'll take good care
of her, I promise.

26:27.620 --> 26:29.889
Knock-knock.
Oh, no! Not again.

26:29.889 --> 26:32.892
Knock-knock. Boo.

26:32.892 --> 26:36.062
[general chatter]

26:41.000 --> 26:42.969
She's bringing two babies.
Two babies?

26:42.969 --> 26:46.238
She's got a new baby,
four months old.

27:32.118 --> 27:35.755
â™ª [guitar]

29:34.974 --> 29:36.342
Smells good.

29:38.944 --> 29:42.314
I was going to go
for a ski, but I thought
I shouldn't chance it,

29:42.314 --> 29:45.017
what with the Alzheimer's
and all.

29:45.017 --> 29:46.152
Why didn't you wake me?

29:46.152 --> 29:47.987
What are these, Grant?

29:57.296 --> 30:00.132
Those are the documents
you're supposed to sign

30:00.132 --> 30:03.002
if you decide
to go to Meadowlake.

30:03.002 --> 30:05.070
That is exactly
what I have decided.

30:05.070 --> 30:07.973
You were to go an sign these
and leave them there.

30:07.973 --> 30:11.577
I wouldn't be allowed
to visit you for 30 days.

30:19.018 --> 30:21.220
30 days isn't
such a long time

30:21.220 --> 30:24.423
after 44 years.

30:24.423 --> 30:26.358
I don't think
I like the place.

30:30.930 --> 30:36.468
I don't think we should
be looking for something
we like, Grant.

30:36.468 --> 30:39.605
I don't think
we'll ever find that.

30:41.040 --> 30:43.609
I think all we can aspire
to in this situation

30:43.609 --> 30:46.245
is a little bit of grace.

30:53.953 --> 30:56.488
Hmm?

30:58.257 --> 31:02.595
â™ª Come a little bit closer â™ª

31:02.595 --> 31:06.565
â™ª Hear what I have to say â™ª

31:15.241 --> 31:19.578
â™ª Just like children
sleeping â™ª

31:19.578 --> 31:23.949
â™ª We can dream
this night away â™ª

31:30.456 --> 31:33.492
I suppose I'll be
dressed up all the time.

31:35.160 --> 31:40.099
It will be sort of like...
in a hotel.

31:44.336 --> 31:45.938
How do I look?

31:45.938 --> 31:47.206
Just like always.

31:47.206 --> 31:48.907
Just as you've
always looked.

31:48.907 --> 31:50.976
And how does that look?

31:53.212 --> 31:55.114
Direct and vague...

31:56.582 --> 31:59.051
sweet and ironic.

32:04.990 --> 32:07.559
Is that how I look?

32:10.496 --> 32:15.534
[on radio]
â™ª Because I'm still
in love with you â™ª

32:15.534 --> 32:20.039
â™ª I want to see you
dance again â™ª

32:20.039 --> 32:22.274
Oh. Remember?

32:25.110 --> 32:26.979
Surprised, Grant?

32:26.979 --> 32:28.347
No, I'm not surprised.

32:28.347 --> 32:32.051
I'm just grateful
you can remember that.

32:32.051 --> 32:35.154
I'm not all gone, Grant.
Just...

32:35.154 --> 32:37.189
[sigh] going--

32:40.125 --> 32:43.028
There are things
I wish would go away.

32:44.963 --> 32:50.035
But won't. You know.
Things we don't talk about.

32:55.240 --> 32:58.143
You never left me.

32:58.143 --> 32:59.345
You still made love to me,

32:59.345 --> 33:02.047
despite disturbing
demands elsewhere.

33:06.285 --> 33:11.490
But all those sandals, Grant.
All those bare female toes.

33:14.059 --> 33:17.563
What could you do but
be a part of the time
you were a part of?

33:17.563 --> 33:20.232
All those pretty girls.

33:20.232 --> 33:23.068
Didn't seem like anyone
was willing to be left out.

33:25.204 --> 33:26.505
I think you did all right,

33:26.505 --> 33:31.276
compared to some
of your colleagues.

33:31.276 --> 33:33.545
Those who left their wives.

33:36.081 --> 33:38.517
And the women who
wouldn't put up with it.

33:41.754 --> 33:47.092
I think people
are too demanding.

33:47.092 --> 33:50.195
People want to be in love
every single day.

33:50.195 --> 33:55.134
What a liability.
And then that silly girl.

33:55.134 --> 33:57.035
That silly girl Veronica.

33:58.170 --> 34:00.806
Girls that age
are always going around

34:00.806 --> 34:04.276
saying they're going
to kill themselves.

34:04.276 --> 34:06.078
But that was that.

34:08.147 --> 34:09.581
Promised me a new life.

34:09.581 --> 34:12.050
We moved out here,

34:12.050 --> 34:15.320
that is exactly
what you gave me.

34:17.623 --> 34:19.591
How long ago was that?

34:19.591 --> 34:22.728
20 years.

34:22.728 --> 34:24.463
[shuddering]

34:26.799 --> 34:28.734
God, that's shocking.

34:30.702 --> 34:35.340
So you see, I'm going...

34:35.340 --> 34:38.210
but I'm not gone.

34:49.388 --> 34:52.858
â™ª And we were lovers â™ª

34:52.858 --> 34:58.130
â™ª I loved you
with all my heart â™ª

35:06.638 --> 35:09.308
Fiona.
Grant.

35:12.411 --> 35:13.278
Don't go.

35:15.714 --> 35:17.850
That's what is happening,
Grant.

35:17.850 --> 35:21.153
It's happening...right now.

35:51.350 --> 35:52.284
Fiona.

35:54.486 --> 35:56.421
Hello.
I'm checking in today.

35:56.421 --> 35:58.290
My name
is Fiona Andersson.

35:58.290 --> 35:59.291
Yes, Mrs. Andersson.

35:59.291 --> 36:01.493
We have your room
all ready for you.

36:01.493 --> 36:02.928
Perfect.
We'll have our supervisor,

36:02.928 --> 36:04.296
Mrs. Montpelier, show you.

36:04.296 --> 36:06.665
I'll go fetch her.
She's expecting you.

36:06.665 --> 36:07.833
Thank you.

36:09.201 --> 36:10.369
Fiona.

36:11.403 --> 36:12.704
Grant.

36:12.704 --> 36:14.306
I can't go away
from you like this.

36:14.306 --> 36:19.478
We had nothing
to tie us down, Grant.

36:19.478 --> 36:22.414
You could have
just driven away
and forsaken me.

36:22.414 --> 36:24.583
But you didn't.

36:26.451 --> 36:28.220
I thank you for that.

36:32.891 --> 36:35.260
Mrs. Andersson.
Oh, hello.

36:35.260 --> 36:37.262
How do you do?
I'm Madeleine.
Hello.

36:37.262 --> 36:38.864
Should I give
you two a moment?

36:38.864 --> 36:40.732
No, thank you.
Yes, please.

36:40.732 --> 36:42.601
All right, then, well,
we'll get you settled
in your room,

36:42.601 --> 36:44.703
and then I'd like to give you
a tour of the facility.

36:44.703 --> 36:47.439
That'd be lovely.
Thank you.
Right this way.

36:53.612 --> 36:57.482
So, as you can see,
we get a lot
of natural light.

36:58.717 --> 37:01.353
Here we go.

37:08.460 --> 37:11.930
Yes.
This'll do just fine.

37:11.930 --> 37:14.533
Good. I'm so glad
you like it. Now, is--

37:14.533 --> 37:16.234
is this all you brought
with you today?

37:16.234 --> 37:17.970
For now.
We'll see how it goes.

37:19.972 --> 37:23.909
Well, if you need any
help arranging things,
you just let me know.

37:23.909 --> 37:27.579
Thank you,
Mrs. Montpelier.

37:27.579 --> 37:30.782
Now, if you wouldn't mind,
I-I'd like to say good-bye
to my husband.

37:30.782 --> 37:35.420
We haven't been
apart for a month
for the last 44 years.

37:35.420 --> 37:36.688
It could be quite something.

37:45.430 --> 37:47.299
Please, Fiona.

37:50.836 --> 37:52.938
[sigh]
Grant.

37:52.938 --> 37:55.707
Fiona--

37:55.707 --> 37:57.776
You know what I'd like?

38:01.446 --> 38:03.482
I'd like to make love,

38:03.482 --> 38:06.518
and then
I'd like you to go.

38:06.518 --> 38:08.053
Because
I need to stay here,

38:08.053 --> 38:09.888
and if you
make it hard for me,

38:09.888 --> 38:12.524
I might cry so hard
I'll never stop.

38:45.691 --> 38:47.459
Go now.

38:49.961 --> 38:51.663
Go now.

39:37.442 --> 39:38.677
[Woman]
"All of the officers

39:38.677 --> 39:39.845
"were from outside
the local area,

39:39.845 --> 39:41.980
"and it probably had not
entered their minds

39:41.980 --> 39:44.816
"that almost all of us
were named McDonald.

39:44.816 --> 39:47.152
"Nobody moved except for
the shuffling of feet.

39:47.152 --> 39:49.821
The red roo"-- Hey.

39:49.821 --> 39:51.790
Hello, there.
Kristy.
We met on your tour.

39:51.790 --> 39:53.592
How's Mrs. Andersson?
Has she settled in?

39:53.592 --> 39:55.761
I'm wondering
if I could have

39:55.761 --> 39:57.896
a moment of your time
to ask your advice?

39:57.896 --> 40:00.398
Oh, sure. I was just
reading to Mr. Burke here.

40:00.398 --> 40:01.767
Maybe when we finish
this chapter,

40:01.767 --> 40:03.668
I can come find you
in the dining room?

40:03.668 --> 40:05.670
Sure. That's fine.

40:07.639 --> 40:10.776
Mm-- "The red roof lights
revolved in the afternoon sun,

40:10.776 --> 40:12.878
and even the dogs were
temporarily quiet."

40:27.726 --> 40:31.830
Hi, there, Mr. Andersson.
Now, how can I help you?

40:31.830 --> 40:33.732
Going down the center
of the dining room--

40:33.732 --> 40:36.868
That's Frank. He used
to be the play-by-play guy
for the Winnipeg Jets.

40:36.868 --> 40:38.970
Really?
Yeah.

40:38.970 --> 40:41.940
He loved his job
too much to retire.

40:41.940 --> 40:43.875
Frank's
on the second floor.

40:47.846 --> 40:52.617
I just--
My wife has always been

40:52.617 --> 40:55.754
sort of a different
sort of person.

40:55.754 --> 41:00.692
I've been told
that Alzheimer's can't be
confirmed until after--

41:00.692 --> 41:02.994
And on our way here today,

41:02.994 --> 41:04.729
we passed
this conservation area

41:04.729 --> 41:08.133
where we went
for a walk last spring.

41:08.133 --> 41:10.569
And there were these
gorgeous flowers.
The skunk lilies.

41:10.569 --> 41:12.504
Oh, those are
beautiful, aren't they?

41:12.504 --> 41:15.140
Yes, they really made
an impression, see?

41:15.140 --> 41:17.742
And even though the whole
place was covered in snow,

41:17.742 --> 41:20.245
she said, "Oh, remember?"

41:21.947 --> 41:25.116
Now, that was--
that was...quite recently.

41:25.116 --> 41:27.085
And isn't
the short-term memory

41:27.085 --> 41:28.820
the thing
that goes first?

41:28.820 --> 41:33.124
Well, yeah,
but not all at once.

41:33.124 --> 41:34.893
And what's comforting

41:34.893 --> 41:36.561
is the long-term memory
sometimes stays

41:36.561 --> 41:37.562
for quite a long time.

41:39.998 --> 41:43.101
Yeah, her long-term memory
seems quite intact.

41:43.101 --> 41:46.705
But when she mentioned that,
about the skunk lilies,

41:46.705 --> 41:49.808
it was all I could do not
to turn the truck around.

41:49.808 --> 41:56.214
What if this is just her
just being herself?

41:56.214 --> 41:58.750
She's far too young to--

42:00.085 --> 42:01.887
She is young.

42:01.887 --> 42:04.890
And it is hard.

42:04.890 --> 42:07.692
No doubt about that.

42:07.692 --> 42:09.828
A month is
a real long time.

42:12.530 --> 42:15.767
I mean, between
you and me, I don't know
about the policy myself.

42:15.767 --> 42:18.770
I think it makes it
easier for the staff
is what I think.

42:18.770 --> 42:22.908
Look. I'll give you
my pager number.

42:24.309 --> 42:25.977
You can call me
whenever you want.

42:25.977 --> 42:28.713
You can call me every day
if you feel like it.

42:32.017 --> 42:34.286
I don't know what to do.

42:36.054 --> 42:38.990
Mr. Andersson, your wife
wrote you this note,

42:38.990 --> 42:41.226
and she asked me
to pass it along.

42:51.303 --> 42:52.737
Okay.

42:58.843 --> 43:00.979
Thank you so much.

43:12.691 --> 43:15.193
[no audible dialogue]

43:25.837 --> 43:28.873
[Grant reading]
"Throughout much of
the thinking brain,

43:28.873 --> 43:34.179
gooey plaques now crowd
neurons from outside
the cell membranes."

43:36.014 --> 43:38.750
"And knotty tangles

43:38.750 --> 43:43.822
mangle microtubal transports
from inside the cells."

43:52.630 --> 43:56.868
"All told, tens of millions
of synapses dissolve away."

43:58.970 --> 44:02.007
"Because the structures
and substructures of the brain

44:02.007 --> 44:03.975
"are so highly specialized,

44:03.975 --> 44:08.079
"the precise location
of the neuronal loss

44:08.079 --> 44:13.985
determines
what specific abilities
will become impaired."

44:18.323 --> 44:23.128
"It is like a series
of circuit breakers

44:23.128 --> 44:27.999
in a large house,
flipping off one by one."

45:27.192 --> 45:29.060
That's a great-looking
coffee maker.

45:29.060 --> 45:31.129
I always meant
to get one of those.

45:32.964 --> 45:36.334
I saw they had them on sale
at Canadian Tire.

45:36.334 --> 45:39.904
They gave it to us,
my son and his wife.

45:39.904 --> 45:41.940
They live in Kamloops, B.C.

45:41.940 --> 45:45.443
They send us more stuff
than we can handle.

45:45.443 --> 45:49.447
Wouldn't hurt
if they spent the money
to come see us instead.

45:51.316 --> 45:53.852
I suppose they're busy
with their own lives.

45:53.852 --> 45:56.321
Not so busy they couldn't
go to Hawaii last year.

45:56.321 --> 45:57.789
I mean,
you could understand it

45:57.789 --> 46:00.925
if there was someone
in the family closer at hand,

46:00.925 --> 46:04.362
but, uh...
he's the only one.

46:08.233 --> 46:12.070
People do get lonely,

46:12.070 --> 46:15.406
especially when
they're deprived of seeing
someone they care about.

46:20.111 --> 46:22.013
Fiona, for instance.

46:24.983 --> 46:26.951
My wife.

46:26.951 --> 46:29.354
I thought you said
you went and visited her.

46:32.023 --> 46:34.092
I do.

46:34.092 --> 46:37.128
No, that's not it.

46:37.128 --> 46:39.063
[Kristy]
She's really settling in well.

46:39.063 --> 46:40.899
Good. Good.

46:40.899 --> 46:42.834
Looking forward to
seeing you tomorrow,
Mr. Andersson.

46:42.834 --> 46:45.103
Right. So I'll see you
tomorrow morning, then.

46:45.103 --> 46:48.139
Now, remember, she may
be a little surprised
to see you.

46:50.208 --> 46:51.943
Don't be shaken by that.

46:51.943 --> 46:54.145
Just-- She hasn't
seen you in a while.

46:54.145 --> 46:56.181
She's sort of
settled in here.

46:58.183 --> 46:59.584
[Grant]
I understand.

47:13.031 --> 47:17.035
There you are. I'll
walk you down to her.

47:17.035 --> 47:19.337
Wow. Narcissus
this early.

47:19.337 --> 47:21.539
You must have spent
a fortune.

47:21.539 --> 47:24.242
We brought it back here.
Hi, Mr. Andersson.

47:24.242 --> 47:26.211
It's great to see you.

47:26.211 --> 47:29.113
I'm gonna help you find
your sweater, Mrs. Albright.

47:29.113 --> 47:32.984
All right. Here we are.
There is her room,
right over there.

47:32.984 --> 47:35.053
You remember from last time
you were here, don't you?

47:35.053 --> 47:38.289
Her nameplate's
right on the door.
I'll leave you to it.

48:19.564 --> 48:22.967
There she is. Now you just
go over and say hello,

48:22.967 --> 48:27.038
and try not to startle her--
Remember, she may not--

48:27.038 --> 48:28.940
Well, just go ahead.

48:48.092 --> 48:51.429
Bridge.
Deadly serious.

48:51.429 --> 48:55.066
Quite rabid about it.

48:55.066 --> 48:58.202
I can remember being
like that at college
for a while.

48:58.202 --> 49:00.638
My friends and I
would cut class

49:00.638 --> 49:03.341
and sit
in the common room
and smoke

49:03.341 --> 49:05.610
and play like cutthroats.

49:05.610 --> 49:07.312
One's name was Phoebe.

49:07.312 --> 49:09.147
I don't remember
the others.

49:09.147 --> 49:10.481
Phoebe Hart.

49:10.481 --> 49:13.384
Oh, you knew her, too.

49:13.384 --> 49:16.254
Can I get you something?
A cup of tea?

49:16.254 --> 49:19.324
I'm afraid the coffee's
not up to much here.

49:19.324 --> 49:20.325
I don't drink tea.

49:20.325 --> 49:22.593
Oh.

49:22.593 --> 49:24.228
I brought you some flowers.

49:24.228 --> 49:27.298
I thought they might do
to brighten up your room.

49:27.298 --> 49:29.467
I went to your room,
but you weren't there.

49:29.467 --> 49:32.203
Well, no, I'm here.

49:35.039 --> 49:36.240
So you've made a new friend.

49:37.542 --> 49:40.211
Oh, that's just Aubrey.

49:40.211 --> 49:45.583
The funny thing is I knew
him years and years ago.

49:45.583 --> 49:47.118
He used to work in the store,

49:47.118 --> 49:51.155
the hardware store where
my grandpa used to shop.

49:51.155 --> 49:54.158
He and I were always
kidding around,

49:54.158 --> 49:57.395
but he never could get up
the nerve to ask me out.

49:57.395 --> 50:00.765
Until the very last weekend,
he took me to a ball game.

50:00.765 --> 50:05.670
But my grandpa showed up
to drive us home.

50:05.670 --> 50:09.207
I was up visiting
for the summer.

50:09.207 --> 50:12.343
Visiting my grandparents.

50:12.343 --> 50:14.445
They lived in a cottage
on a lake.

50:16.214 --> 50:19.183
Fiona, I know where
your grandparents lived.

50:19.183 --> 50:21.052
It's where we lived.
We live.

50:22.320 --> 50:23.721
Really?

50:25.623 --> 50:27.325
I'd better go back.

50:27.325 --> 50:29.761
He thinks he can't play
without me sitting there.

50:29.761 --> 50:33.030
It's silly. I hardly
know the game anymore.

50:33.030 --> 50:35.233
I'm afraid you'll have
to excuse me.

50:35.233 --> 50:36.200
Will you be through soon?

50:36.200 --> 50:38.202
We should be.
I mean, it depends.

50:38.202 --> 50:41.272
If you asked that grim-looking
lady over there nicely,

50:41.272 --> 50:43.441
she'll get you a cup of tea.

50:45.076 --> 50:46.677
No, I'm fine.
I can leave you, then?

50:46.677 --> 50:50.248
You can entertain yourself?
Must all seem strange to you.

50:50.248 --> 50:53.117
But you'll be surprised
how soon you get used to it.

50:53.117 --> 50:55.453
You'll get to know
who everybody is,

50:55.453 --> 51:00.057
except that some of them
are pretty well off
in the clouds, you know?

51:00.057 --> 51:05.196
Hmm. Can't expect them all
to get to know who you are.

52:24.208 --> 52:27.211
Hey, I've been thinking
of dying my hair.
What do you think?

52:27.211 --> 52:30.414
Do you think I'd look
good with red hair?

52:50.368 --> 52:53.271
You caught her at
sort of a bad moment,
involved in a game.

52:53.271 --> 52:55.439
She isn't even playing.

52:55.439 --> 52:57.708
Well, but her friend's
playing, Aubrey.

52:57.708 --> 52:59.210
Now, who is Aubrey?

52:59.210 --> 53:01.212
That's who he is,
Aubrey.

53:01.212 --> 53:02.680
You know, they get
these attachments.

53:02.680 --> 53:04.715
That kind of takes over
for a while.

53:04.715 --> 53:06.751
Best buddy kind of thing.

53:06.751 --> 53:08.286
Sort of a phase.

53:09.253 --> 53:11.222
Does she even know who I am?

53:12.690 --> 53:14.625
No, she might not.

53:14.625 --> 53:18.462
Not today, and then,
tomorrow you never know.

53:18.462 --> 53:21.432
Things change
back and forth
all the time.

53:21.432 --> 53:22.466
You'll see
the way it is

53:22.466 --> 53:24.335
once you get used
to coming here.

53:24.335 --> 53:25.970
You'll learn
not to take it
so personal.

53:25.970 --> 53:29.307
Learn to take it
day by day.

53:31.576 --> 53:34.345
[inaudible dialogue]

53:51.996 --> 53:53.898
Oh, I'm sorry.

53:53.898 --> 53:56.500
I'll have to go
and fix that now.

54:26.497 --> 54:28.766
[Man, TV]
Here's Yung Menenikenaha,

54:28.766 --> 54:32.570
desperately clinging
to his one-stroke lead.

54:32.570 --> 54:34.372
Here's the swing.

54:34.372 --> 54:36.307
It doesn't look good.

54:36.307 --> 54:38.709
Looks like he's pushed it
out to the right.

54:38.709 --> 54:40.711
It lands 25 feet
from the green.

54:40.711 --> 54:42.546
This must be disappointing.

54:42.546 --> 54:45.016
It doesn't look good
for Yung Menenikenaha.

54:45.016 --> 54:47.385
He was three strokes
on the happy side of par

54:47.385 --> 54:48.452
until these last three holes.

54:53.290 --> 54:57.061
Look at you,
Mr. Andersson.

54:57.061 --> 54:59.664
I think you might
be one of our most
frequent visitors.

55:08.773 --> 55:10.474
Hi, Fiona.

55:10.474 --> 55:12.476
Oh, you are persistent,
aren't you?

55:12.476 --> 55:14.512
I brought you some books.

55:14.512 --> 55:16.881
They don't seem to have
an awful lot around here.

55:16.881 --> 55:19.383
Letters from Iceland
by Auden.

55:19.383 --> 55:22.653
We always meant
to read that together,
didn't we?

55:22.653 --> 55:25.056
Do you think
it'd be possible
to talk alone?

55:25.056 --> 55:26.624
Well, I don't know.

55:26.624 --> 55:29.427
Um, Aubrey's card game
starts in a few minutes,

55:29.427 --> 55:31.095
and then we usually
go walking,

55:31.095 --> 55:32.697
and then he does
his drawing--

55:32.697 --> 55:36.000
Or perhaps you can find
a bit of time later on.

55:36.000 --> 55:37.535
Um, I'll stay here.

55:37.535 --> 55:39.437
Or I'll come back
in a few hours.

55:39.437 --> 55:41.839
Oh, you are persistent,
aren't you?

56:04.595 --> 56:06.497
[Man, TV]
Up comes Kapanen--
Boy, oh, boy!

56:06.497 --> 56:08.532
[Frank]
Here we are at the Spectrum
in Philadelphia.

56:08.532 --> 56:10.801
It's sudden-death overtime.
They're tied 2-2.

56:10.801 --> 56:12.503
Here are the Leafs again,
led by Andreychuk.

56:12.503 --> 56:13.738
He carries it
over the blue line,

56:13.738 --> 56:15.706
winds up a shot right on!

56:15.706 --> 56:17.608
The bounce, the rebound
comes back behind the net.

56:17.608 --> 56:18.909
McCabe couldn't get to it.

56:18.909 --> 56:20.478
It goes back
on the left wing

56:20.478 --> 56:22.913
and here come the Flyers
led by Roenick again.

56:22.913 --> 56:25.516
Roenick and Mitchell,
what a twosome
this two has been.

56:25.516 --> 56:26.884
A shot right on!
Oh, it just went wide.

56:26.884 --> 56:28.686
Go for it, Frank.
Over to the right side.

56:28.686 --> 56:29.987
Here we go again.
The Leafs again.

56:29.987 --> 56:32.523
Here's Sundin carrying it
up over the line.

56:32.523 --> 56:35.526
Can't get a shot away
and it's cleared away
by Philadelphia.

56:35.526 --> 56:37.728
A loose puck
grabbed by Philadelphia
over on the left wing--

56:37.728 --> 56:40.598
I just came down to say
Aubrey is having his nap

56:40.598 --> 56:42.800
if you'd like to, um, talk.

56:42.800 --> 56:44.735
Oh, sure.

56:44.735 --> 56:46.804
Can we go somewhere
a little more private?

56:46.804 --> 56:48.506
[Frank]
...the side with Mitchell.
He shoots, he scores!

56:48.506 --> 56:49.907
If-- If you'd like.

56:49.907 --> 56:51.542
[Frank]
And Philly wins this series

56:51.542 --> 56:52.743
by a score of 3-2.

56:52.743 --> 56:54.678
That's it this season
for the Leafs.

56:54.678 --> 56:56.914
Look at Phil Hitchcock.
Is he a happy coach.

56:56.914 --> 56:58.849
Philadelphia wins 3-2.

56:58.849 --> 57:00.718
The game is over
in sudden-death overtime.

57:21.772 --> 57:24.141
Y-You said you had
some books for me?

57:24.141 --> 57:25.743
This.

57:27.578 --> 57:29.480
Letters from Iceland.

57:29.480 --> 57:33.083
Yes, yes.
You said by Auden.

57:33.083 --> 57:35.553
Yes. That's right.

57:35.553 --> 57:38.823
Now...where is Iceland?

57:42.092 --> 57:46.630
Well, Iceland
is in the middle
of the Atlantic.

57:46.630 --> 57:48.966
It's an island.

57:50.668 --> 57:52.903
Youngest country
in the world.

57:52.903 --> 57:55.206
It's constantly erupting.

57:55.206 --> 57:58.809
Volcanoes, earthquakes.

57:58.809 --> 58:02.847
It's always
shaking itself off.

58:04.014 --> 58:07.484
Wouldn't it be nice to come
from a young country?

58:07.484 --> 58:09.753
You do.
That's where you're from.

58:09.753 --> 58:13.090
That's where
your people are from.

58:13.090 --> 58:17.728
They immigrated here
in the late 1800s.

58:17.728 --> 58:20.497
But that's where
you're from, Fiona.

58:20.497 --> 58:25.836
And I teach-- Well, I taught
the myths from there.

58:25.836 --> 58:27.004
Norse mythology.

58:27.004 --> 58:28.739
I-I must have
been there, then.

58:28.739 --> 58:30.541
Have I been there?

58:30.541 --> 58:31.609
[sniffs]

58:31.609 --> 58:32.676
No.

58:34.578 --> 58:35.980
Oh.

58:35.980 --> 58:38.616
Why not?
Wasn't I curious?

58:38.616 --> 58:41.719
You were very curious.

58:41.719 --> 58:44.221
Very curious.

58:44.221 --> 58:48.259
You always said
there ought to be one place

58:48.259 --> 58:50.895
that you knew about
and you thought about

58:50.895 --> 58:52.863
and maybe even longed for,

58:52.863 --> 58:54.932
but you did never did
get to see.

59:01.572 --> 59:04.241
Did I say that?

59:04.241 --> 59:06.176
Yes, you said that.

59:20.991 --> 59:23.227
Well, I'd better
go and see to Aubrey.

59:23.227 --> 59:25.863
He'll be wanting a little
walk around, I suppose.

59:25.863 --> 59:26.964
It was nice chatting.

59:26.964 --> 59:29.800
You'll be back again
tomorrow, I suppose?

59:29.800 --> 59:33.637
Fiona, what are you doing--

59:33.637 --> 59:34.972
What are you doing
with Aubrey?

59:38.275 --> 59:41.979
He doesn't confuse me.

59:41.979 --> 59:44.615
He doesn't confuse me
at all.

59:48.886 --> 59:52.089
Well,
it's been nice chatting.

59:52.089 --> 59:54.892
I'll see you again
tomorrow, I suppose.

59:57.695 --> 1:00:02.032
[door opens, closes]

1:00:14.778 --> 1:00:17.648
[Grant]
These affections
between residents,

1:00:17.648 --> 1:00:18.816
do they ever go too far?

1:00:18.816 --> 1:00:20.117
[Kristy chuckles]

1:00:20.117 --> 1:00:21.852
Well, that depends
on what you mean.

1:00:21.852 --> 1:00:24.655
The problem we have here,
it's funny.

1:00:24.655 --> 1:00:26.290
It's actually
often the ones

1:00:26.290 --> 1:00:28.792
who haven't been friendly
with each other at all.

1:00:28.792 --> 1:00:30.294
I mean, they maybe
don't even know each other

1:00:30.294 --> 1:00:32.997
beyond knowing, like,
is it a man or is it a woman?

1:00:32.997 --> 1:00:34.098
And you'd think
it'd be the old guys

1:00:34.098 --> 1:00:36.133
trying to crawl in bed
with the old ladies,

1:00:36.133 --> 1:00:37.968
but half the time
it's the other way around.

1:00:37.968 --> 1:00:40.871
It's the old ladies
going after the old men.

1:00:40.871 --> 1:00:42.806
It could be they aren't
so worn out.

1:00:42.806 --> 1:00:44.875
[chuckling]

1:00:50.047 --> 1:00:54.752
Now don't get me wrong.
I don't mean Fiona.

1:00:54.752 --> 1:00:56.887
Fiona is a lady.

1:00:56.887 --> 1:00:59.256
She's a real lady.

1:01:00.791 --> 1:01:04.228
I sometimes wonder--

1:01:04.228 --> 1:01:06.296
You wonder what?

1:01:08.866 --> 1:01:14.138
I wonder if she isn't
putting on some kind
of...charade.

1:01:14.138 --> 1:01:16.040
A what?

1:01:16.040 --> 1:01:19.076
Some kind of act.

1:01:19.076 --> 1:01:22.312
Maybe some kind of punishment.

1:01:25.949 --> 1:01:27.951
Why would she do that?

1:01:34.691 --> 1:01:36.193
Oh.

1:02:05.389 --> 1:02:07.357
[Fiona]
Are you getting tired?

1:02:07.357 --> 1:02:08.926
[Aubrey]
No.
[Fiona]
Are you certain--

1:02:15.933 --> 1:02:18.268
Excuse me.

1:02:18.268 --> 1:02:20.437
Yes, Mr. Andersson?

1:02:20.437 --> 1:02:23.073
How can I help you?

1:02:23.073 --> 1:02:24.875
Fiona's wearing
someone else's sweater.

1:02:24.875 --> 1:02:27.311
[Madeleine]
Well, it's pretty,
isn't it?

1:02:27.311 --> 1:02:28.879
No, it's not pretty.
It's tacky.

1:02:28.879 --> 1:02:31.915
She would never wear it.
Well, I'll tell you what.

1:02:31.915 --> 1:02:33.383
You can talk
to the duty attendant

1:02:33.383 --> 1:02:35.152
on Mrs. Andersson's
wing.

1:02:35.152 --> 1:02:37.387
Boy, it's a marvel, really,

1:02:37.387 --> 1:02:39.923
the way she's getting him up
and out of that chair.

1:02:46.797 --> 1:02:48.198
Can you manage?

1:02:50.934 --> 1:02:52.302
Will you be all right?

1:02:52.302 --> 1:02:54.271
I'll
be back in a second.

1:02:57.040 --> 1:02:59.443
Fiona,
I'm your husband.

1:02:59.443 --> 1:03:01.311
Fiona, it's Grant.

1:03:01.311 --> 1:03:03.814
We've been married
for 45 years.

1:03:03.814 --> 1:03:07.217
Look at me, Fiona.
That is not your sweater.

1:03:07.217 --> 1:03:09.119
We had a good life
together.

1:03:09.119 --> 1:03:12.055
Those are your words,
Fiona, not mine.

1:03:12.055 --> 1:03:14.091
That is not your sweater.

1:03:14.091 --> 1:03:17.227
[Aubrey groaning]

1:03:20.130 --> 1:03:22.399
It's all right.

1:03:22.399 --> 1:03:25.269
It's all right.
It's all right.

1:03:25.269 --> 1:03:27.204
I'm coming
straight back.

1:03:27.204 --> 1:03:28.372
I'm coming
straight back.

1:03:28.372 --> 1:03:30.574
It's going to be
all right.

1:03:49.193 --> 1:03:52.296
I'll see you again
tomorrow, I suppose.

1:03:56.200 --> 1:03:58.101
Please...

1:03:59.570 --> 1:04:00.504
don't.

1:04:03.373 --> 1:04:06.343
Please, please don't.

1:04:09.846 --> 1:04:12.416
You're very persistent,
aren't you?

1:04:18.855 --> 1:04:22.226
I wish I--

1:04:22.226 --> 1:04:23.961
Wish I knew what--

1:04:29.499 --> 1:04:33.070
[sniffles]

1:04:33.070 --> 1:04:35.872
We'll see you again
tomorrow, I suppose.

1:05:19.182 --> 1:05:22.219
You're not doing
too well, are you?

1:05:22.219 --> 1:05:23.920
Well, no big surprise.

1:05:23.920 --> 1:05:27.090
What we're handling
isn't so easy.

1:05:29.259 --> 1:05:30.627
I thought
when I married,

1:05:30.627 --> 1:05:34.264
I'd be with someone
to the final stretch.

1:05:34.264 --> 1:05:37.434
I'm betting
you thought the same.

1:05:37.434 --> 1:05:39.636
Well, didn't work out.

1:05:39.636 --> 1:05:43.507
[Aubrey groaning]

1:05:43.507 --> 1:05:48.178
So, I, uh, think
you're here for a reason.

1:05:48.178 --> 1:05:51.648
I'm the kind of person
you can say things
flat out to, so shoot.

1:05:51.648 --> 1:05:55.652
[sigh]

1:05:55.652 --> 1:05:58.989
I wonder if you would
consider taking Aubrey
back to Meadowlake,

1:05:58.989 --> 1:06:02.025
maybe just for a visit.

1:06:02.025 --> 1:06:05.429
Or I suppose
I could take Aubrey
out there myself.

1:06:05.429 --> 1:06:07.164
I wouldn't mind that at all.

1:06:09.466 --> 1:06:11.168
[sigh]

1:06:12.269 --> 1:06:13.970
Homemade.

1:06:21.211 --> 1:06:22.245
Really?

1:06:25.215 --> 1:06:29.086
No. No, I can't do that.

1:06:29.086 --> 1:06:31.221
And the reason is
I don't want to upset him.

1:06:31.221 --> 1:06:32.723
But wouldn't he understand
it was just a visit?

1:06:32.723 --> 1:06:35.592
He understands everything.

1:06:35.592 --> 1:06:38.195
Now, if I go
to all that trouble,

1:06:38.195 --> 1:06:40.764
I'd prefer to take him
someplace that'd be
more fun, hmm?

1:06:40.764 --> 1:06:43.367
It would make more sense
to take him to the mall

1:06:43.367 --> 1:06:44.735
where there are kids
and whatnot.

1:06:44.735 --> 1:06:47.237
And then I'd have to
get him all ready,

1:06:47.237 --> 1:06:48.739
maneuver him
into the car.

1:06:48.739 --> 1:06:51.208
He's a big man.
He's not that easy
to manage.

1:06:51.208 --> 1:06:53.310
Even if I agreed to do it?

1:06:53.310 --> 1:06:54.578
You couldn't do it.
You don't know him.

1:06:54.578 --> 1:06:56.213
You couldn't manage him.

1:06:56.213 --> 1:06:58.281
And he wouldn't stand
your doing for him.

1:06:58.281 --> 1:07:03.120
And after all that,
what would he get
out of it?

1:07:03.120 --> 1:07:04.254
Uh...

1:07:05.455 --> 1:07:07.057
Hmm.

1:07:26.410 --> 1:07:27.811
Smoke?

1:07:27.811 --> 1:07:30.180
No. No, thanks.

1:07:30.180 --> 1:07:32.315
What, did you never,
or did you quit?

1:07:32.315 --> 1:07:33.583
I quit.

1:07:33.583 --> 1:07:34.818
How long ago?

1:07:34.818 --> 1:07:39.589
Oh, 30 years,
maybe more.

1:07:39.589 --> 1:07:41.224
I quit quitting.

1:07:43.527 --> 1:07:46.496
Just made a resolution
to quit quitting,
that's all.

1:07:48.165 --> 1:07:51.334
So your wife's
depressed, huh?

1:07:52.302 --> 1:07:54.504
What's her name again?
I forget.

1:07:54.504 --> 1:07:56.239
Fiona.

1:07:56.239 --> 1:07:58.508
[Kristy]
And how old were you
when you met?

1:07:58.508 --> 1:08:00.610
She was 18.

1:08:00.610 --> 1:08:03.380
Holy, that's pretty young
to get married, eh?

1:08:03.380 --> 1:08:05.081
[chuckling]

1:08:07.484 --> 1:08:08.819
Wasn't my idea.

1:08:08.819 --> 1:08:11.354
You mean
she proposed to you?

1:08:11.354 --> 1:08:13.089
Well, that's lovely,
that's what I think.

1:08:13.089 --> 1:08:13.857
How'd she do it?

1:08:13.857 --> 1:08:16.526
She hadn't planned it
necessarily.

1:08:16.526 --> 1:08:20.363
We were in Tobermory
waiting for the ferry
to Manitoulin,

1:08:20.363 --> 1:08:23.266
and it was miserable
and rainy,

1:08:23.266 --> 1:08:27.137
and she was in a good mood.

1:08:27.137 --> 1:08:29.139
She didn't want any part
of my sour mood.

1:08:29.139 --> 1:08:31.541
[chuckles]
And what'd she do,
what'd she say?

1:08:31.541 --> 1:08:36.413
Well, she said,
"Do you think it'd be fun--

1:08:36.413 --> 1:08:40.250
Do you think it'd be fun
if we got married?"

1:08:40.250 --> 1:08:41.751
And what did you say?

1:08:41.751 --> 1:08:43.353
I took her up on it.

1:08:43.353 --> 1:08:45.222
I shouted yes.

1:08:49.893 --> 1:08:52.562
I never wanted
to be away from her.

1:08:54.731 --> 1:08:57.200
She had the spark of life.

1:08:59.269 --> 1:09:01.338
[Kristy]
You know, nothing
can take away

1:09:01.338 --> 1:09:05.742
what's happened to you
and what you've experienced.

1:09:05.742 --> 1:09:07.444
I don't think so, anyway.

1:09:07.444 --> 1:09:12.749
Even if it goes away somehow,
it's still there.

1:09:12.749 --> 1:09:14.885
It's still what you are.

1:09:16.853 --> 1:09:18.488
[Grant]
It's curious.

1:09:18.488 --> 1:09:19.623
What's curious?

1:09:19.623 --> 1:09:23.226
All of that
"madly in love" business.

1:09:23.226 --> 1:09:24.694
The beginning.

1:09:24.694 --> 1:09:30.400
I hear myself tell the story,
and it all sounds so crucial.

1:09:32.235 --> 1:09:33.937
I suppose it is.

1:09:33.937 --> 1:09:36.406
But compared to what
we ended up with,

1:09:36.406 --> 1:09:38.675
until recently...

1:09:40.644 --> 1:09:44.447
all of that seems
so superficial somehow.

1:09:46.683 --> 1:09:49.586
[chatter,
plates clinking]

1:10:22.652 --> 1:10:26.356
â™ª [heavy metal]

1:10:26.356 --> 1:10:29.993
Not such a fun place
to visit, eh?

1:10:29.993 --> 1:10:31.328
Excuse me?

1:10:31.328 --> 1:10:34.798
Not such a fun place
to visit.

1:10:34.798 --> 1:10:36.433
Fucking depressing.

1:10:38.468 --> 1:10:39.536
No offense.

1:10:39.536 --> 1:10:40.637
None taken.

1:10:42.639 --> 1:10:45.942
No one came
to visit you, huh?

1:10:45.942 --> 1:10:47.911
That must suck huge.

1:10:47.911 --> 1:10:51.514
Well, it would suck huge,
but I don't live here.

1:10:51.514 --> 1:10:53.683
I'm just visiting someone.

1:10:53.683 --> 1:10:55.986
Who? Which one?

1:10:55.986 --> 1:10:59.422
Beautiful woman
with the shock of hair.

1:10:59.422 --> 1:11:00.690
The one sitting
with her husband?

1:11:00.690 --> 1:11:03.493
You might say that.
Why wouldn't you?

1:11:03.493 --> 1:11:05.562
I wouldn't say that
because I'm her husband.

1:11:07.564 --> 1:11:10.367
So why aren't you
sitting with her, then?

1:11:13.436 --> 1:11:16.773
Just learned to give her
some space.

1:11:16.773 --> 1:11:19.275
She's in love with that man
she's sitting with.

1:11:19.275 --> 1:11:21.578
I don't like to disturb her.

1:11:21.578 --> 1:11:24.047
I just like to see her,
I suppose.

1:11:24.047 --> 1:11:27.584
Make sure she's
doing well, you know?

1:11:30.654 --> 1:11:33.623
I suppose that must seem
rather pathetic.

1:11:35.425 --> 1:11:37.761
I should be so lucky.

1:11:43.900 --> 1:11:45.435
Come on.

1:11:47.070 --> 1:11:48.638
[chuckles]

1:12:10.393 --> 1:12:11.995
She's not here.

1:12:11.995 --> 1:12:13.763
She's sick.

1:12:13.763 --> 1:12:16.466
He's not here, either.

1:12:16.466 --> 1:12:18.535
[laughing]

1:12:34.584 --> 1:12:36.453
[knocking]

1:12:44.761 --> 1:12:48.531
I brought you a book.

1:12:48.531 --> 1:12:50.734
It's all about Iceland.

1:12:50.734 --> 1:12:53.136
Thought you might like
to take a look at it.

1:12:53.136 --> 1:12:55.438
Why, thank you.

1:12:55.438 --> 1:12:56.539
[crying]

1:12:56.539 --> 1:12:59.576
Oh, what is it,
dear heart?

1:12:59.576 --> 1:13:02.445
[Aubrey sniffling]
What is it?
Oh, I see.

1:13:02.445 --> 1:13:04.748
Here. Here.
Here.

1:13:04.748 --> 1:13:07.050
Here, here, yes.

1:13:09.819 --> 1:13:12.789
Do you by any chance have
any influence around here?

1:13:12.789 --> 1:13:16.659
I've seen you
talking to them.

1:13:18.661 --> 1:13:20.697
Oh.

1:13:23.566 --> 1:13:24.701
We'll get to see each other.

1:13:24.701 --> 1:13:28.571
[groans]
You'll see.
We have to.

1:13:28.571 --> 1:13:31.608
I'll come and see you,

1:13:31.608 --> 1:13:34.110
and you'll come
and see me.

1:13:41.050 --> 1:13:42.619
You know,
I just wish his wife

1:13:42.619 --> 1:13:44.154
would hurry up
and get here.

1:13:44.154 --> 1:13:46.089
I wish she'd
get him out of here

1:13:46.089 --> 1:13:47.590
and cut the agony
short.

1:13:47.590 --> 1:13:49.025
Should I stay?

1:13:49.025 --> 1:13:51.861
Don't worry.
She's not sick,
you know.

1:13:53.997 --> 1:13:55.732
To keep her company.

1:13:55.732 --> 1:13:58.468
Well, they have to learn
to get over these things
by themselves.

1:13:58.468 --> 1:14:01.905
They've got short memories,
and that's not always so bad.

1:14:04.607 --> 1:14:05.775
Okay?

1:14:31.734 --> 1:14:35.872
[Woman]
Fiona. Her name is Fiona.

1:14:35.872 --> 1:14:37.240
And what's yours?

1:14:37.240 --> 1:14:40.543
I don't think
I was ever told that.

1:14:40.543 --> 1:14:43.179
Oh, I'm sorry.
It's Grant.

1:14:43.179 --> 1:14:45.181
Hmm.

1:14:45.181 --> 1:14:47.617
Hello, Grant.

1:14:47.617 --> 1:14:49.686
I'm Marian.

1:14:53.223 --> 1:14:56.526
Well, now that we know
each other's name,

1:14:56.526 --> 1:15:00.730
I can
tell you straight out
what I'm thinking.

1:15:00.730 --> 1:15:05.802
I don't know if he's still
so stuck on seeing your--

1:15:05.802 --> 1:15:06.936
seeing Fiona.

1:15:06.936 --> 1:15:09.806
I don't ask him,
he doesn't tell me.

1:15:09.806 --> 1:15:13.142
But I don't feel like
putting him back in there

1:15:13.142 --> 1:15:15.745
in case it turns out
to be more than that.

1:15:15.745 --> 1:15:18.615
I don't want him
getting hard to handle.

1:15:18.615 --> 1:15:22.185
I don't have any help.
It's just me here.

1:15:22.185 --> 1:15:23.653
I'm it.

1:15:23.653 --> 1:15:24.954
It is very hard for you.

1:15:24.954 --> 1:15:27.857
Did-- Did you ever consider
his going in there for good?

1:15:27.857 --> 1:15:30.894
No. I'm keeping him
right here.

1:15:30.894 --> 1:15:33.596
Well, that's very good
and noble of you.

1:15:33.596 --> 1:15:34.898
Oh, you think so?

1:15:34.898 --> 1:15:38.968
Well, noble is not
what I'm thinking about.

1:15:38.968 --> 1:15:40.970
No, but it isn't easy.

1:15:40.970 --> 1:15:43.306
No, it isn't,
but I don't have a choice.

1:15:43.306 --> 1:15:47.143
If I pay to put him in there,
I won't hold on to the house,

1:15:47.143 --> 1:15:49.679
and the house
is the only thing
we own outright.

1:15:52.315 --> 1:15:56.619
And it means a lot to me,
this house does.

1:15:56.619 --> 1:15:58.121
It's very nice.

1:15:59.088 --> 1:16:02.191
Well, I guess it's all right.

1:16:02.191 --> 1:16:05.895
I've done a lot on it,
fixing it up, keeping it up.

1:16:05.895 --> 1:16:07.931
Yes, I can see
that you have-- you do.

1:16:07.931 --> 1:16:09.832
I don't want to lose it.
No.

1:16:09.832 --> 1:16:12.068
I'm not going to lose it.
I see your point.

1:16:12.068 --> 1:16:14.070
See, the company
left us high and dry.

1:16:14.070 --> 1:16:20.109
In the end, they said
he owed them money.

1:16:21.711 --> 1:16:26.582
What do I think?
Well, he was pretty stupid.

1:16:26.582 --> 1:16:27.717
[sigh]

1:16:27.717 --> 1:16:31.821
But I'm not supposed
to ask, so I shut up.

1:16:31.821 --> 1:16:33.289
You've been married, huh?

1:16:33.289 --> 1:16:36.192
I mean, you are married.
You know what it's like.

1:16:37.961 --> 1:16:40.163
And then, in the middle
of all this,

1:16:40.163 --> 1:16:45.168
he gets sick from this virus,
and he goes into a coma.

1:16:50.173 --> 1:16:54.978
So that pretty much
takes him off the hook, hmm?

1:16:57.246 --> 1:16:58.848
It's bad luck.

1:16:59.983 --> 1:17:02.852
It's, no, just life.

1:17:06.622 --> 1:17:08.191
Can't beat life.

1:17:09.892 --> 1:17:11.227
No.

1:17:15.365 --> 1:17:16.833
[knocking at door]

1:17:23.106 --> 1:17:25.708
Oh. Hello.

1:18:07.383 --> 1:18:09.118
Perhaps you'd like me
to read to you.

1:18:11.254 --> 1:18:13.456
I don't have any books.

1:18:16.959 --> 1:18:18.361
Oh, there are some.

1:18:20.997 --> 1:18:23.066
Letters from Iceland.

1:18:32.308 --> 1:18:34.977
"Isn't it true,
however far we've wandered

1:18:34.977 --> 1:18:37.814
"into our provinces
of persecution,

1:18:37.814 --> 1:18:41.984
"where our regrets accuse,
we keep returning

1:18:41.984 --> 1:18:44.087
"back to the common faith

1:18:44.087 --> 1:18:46.289
"from which
we've all dissented,

1:18:46.289 --> 1:18:50.293
"back to the hands,
the feet, the faces?

1:18:50.293 --> 1:18:54.030
"Children are always there
and take the hands,

1:18:54.030 --> 1:18:55.998
"even when they
are most terrified.

1:18:55.998 --> 1:19:00.236
"Those in love cannot
make up their minds
to go or stay.

1:19:00.236 --> 1:19:03.806
"Artist and doctor
return most often.

1:19:03.806 --> 1:19:07.043
"Only the mad will never,
never come back.

1:19:07.043 --> 1:19:09.879
"For doctors keep
on worrying while away,

1:19:09.879 --> 1:19:14.784
"in case their skill
is suffering and deserted.

1:19:14.784 --> 1:19:18.754
"Lovers have lived so long
with giants and elves,

1:19:18.754 --> 1:19:22.325
"they want belief again
in their own size.

1:19:22.325 --> 1:19:25.394
"And the artist prays
ever so gently,

1:19:25.394 --> 1:19:29.132
"'Let me find pure
all that can happen.

1:19:29.132 --> 1:19:32.368
"'Only uniqueness is success.

1:19:32.368 --> 1:19:36.939
"'For instance,
let me perceive
the images of history.

1:19:36.939 --> 1:19:41.010
"'All that I push away
with doubt and travel,

1:19:41.010 --> 1:19:45.081
today's and yesterday's alike,
like bodies."

1:19:45.081 --> 1:19:48.084
[George W. Bush]
To all the men and women of
the United States Armed Forces

1:19:48.084 --> 1:19:50.419
now in the Middle East,
the peace of a troubled world

1:19:50.419 --> 1:19:52.855
and the hopes
of an oppressed people

1:19:52.855 --> 1:19:56.092
now depend on you.

1:19:56.092 --> 1:19:57.927
How could they forget Vietnam?

1:19:57.927 --> 1:20:00.296
[Woman]
The air strike started again
at 5 A.M. this morning

1:20:00.296 --> 1:20:02.298
and lasted for three hours.

1:20:02.298 --> 1:20:04.167
Roadside explosions
have killed

1:20:04.167 --> 1:20:07.537
eight Iraqi civilians
and one U.S. soldier.

1:20:09.071 --> 1:20:10.806
Hmm.
Hmm.

1:20:17.113 --> 1:20:18.214
Here you go.

1:20:19.415 --> 1:20:22.552
Next time you do it,
just go pick it up, okay?

1:20:28.491 --> 1:20:31.227
Her muscles
are deteriorating.

1:20:31.227 --> 1:20:32.228
If she doesn't
improve soon,

1:20:32.228 --> 1:20:35.431
we're going to have to
put her on a walker.

1:20:35.431 --> 1:20:36.966
I keep trying
to get her walking,

1:20:36.966 --> 1:20:39.035
but she doesn't seem
to want to go anywhere.

1:20:39.035 --> 1:20:42.872
But, you know,
once they get on a walker,
they start to depend on it,

1:20:42.872 --> 1:20:44.941
and then they don't want
to walk much anymore,

1:20:44.941 --> 1:20:47.577
just get wherever it is
they have to go.

1:20:47.577 --> 1:20:49.946
You're going to have to
work at her harder.

1:20:49.946 --> 1:20:52.048
Try and encourage her.

1:20:52.048 --> 1:20:53.482
Sorry.

1:20:59.155 --> 1:21:01.023
Here you go.

1:21:13.002 --> 1:21:15.104
Mrs. Andersson.

1:21:15.104 --> 1:21:17.907
How would you like
to go on a field trip?

1:22:00.182 --> 1:22:03.452
They've kept it
so like it was.

1:22:05.921 --> 1:22:08.357
Who has?

1:22:08.357 --> 1:22:10.960
The people who live here.

1:23:20.730 --> 1:23:23.065
But everything...

1:23:29.338 --> 1:23:32.541
Everything
just reminds me of him.

1:23:34.210 --> 1:23:38.280
It wasn't enough,
I suppose.

1:23:38.280 --> 1:23:40.316
Who, Fiona?

1:23:41.684 --> 1:23:44.320
Who does everything
remind you of?

1:24:03.372 --> 1:24:07.209
I'd like to go home now,
if you don't mind.

1:24:12.181 --> 1:24:14.083
[Madeleine]
Now, as you know,

1:24:14.083 --> 1:24:17.253
we don't do extended care
on the first floor.

1:24:17.253 --> 1:24:21.323
I mean, we do it temporarily
if someone isn't feeling well.

1:24:21.323 --> 1:24:24.827
But if they progress
too far,

1:24:24.827 --> 1:24:29.064
we have to consider
moving upstairs.

1:24:30.332 --> 1:24:32.401
[sigh]

1:24:32.401 --> 1:24:35.371
Do you happen to have
Aubrey's address?

1:24:35.371 --> 1:24:37.072
I'm sorry?

1:24:40.075 --> 1:24:43.712
Aubrey and his wife.

1:24:43.712 --> 1:24:46.248
Where do they live?

1:25:03.232 --> 1:25:04.633
[Marian]
Well, it was
probably a mistake

1:25:04.633 --> 1:25:07.236
putting him there
in the first place,

1:25:07.236 --> 1:25:09.438
but I wasn't going
to get another chance

1:25:09.438 --> 1:25:12.508
to get away,
so I took it.

1:25:12.508 --> 1:25:13.742
Well, so...

1:25:15.544 --> 1:25:17.446
[chuckles]
Now I know better.

1:25:20.850 --> 1:25:23.385
Did your husband ever
work in a hardware store

1:25:23.385 --> 1:25:25.588
in the summers
when he was going to school?

1:25:25.588 --> 1:25:29.425
No, I never heard
about that.

1:25:29.425 --> 1:25:31.293
But I wasn't raised here.

1:25:32.728 --> 1:25:36.265
No. I didn't think so.

1:25:43.405 --> 1:25:46.809
Thank you very much
for your time, Miriam.

1:25:46.809 --> 1:25:50.446
It's Marian.

1:25:50.446 --> 1:25:51.614
Sorry.

1:25:59.355 --> 1:26:01.357
[sigh]

1:26:01.357 --> 1:26:03.492
What a jerk.

1:26:09.565 --> 1:26:10.533
Hmm.

1:26:13.168 --> 1:26:15.304
[car engine starts]

1:26:22.945 --> 1:26:24.947
Yeah, maybe someone
could just drop in on her,

1:26:24.947 --> 1:26:26.482
like, if the nurse
is around.

1:26:26.482 --> 1:26:28.884
All right.

1:26:28.884 --> 1:26:30.686
No, I don't think
there's much to it,

1:26:30.686 --> 1:26:32.555
but I'd like you
to call me back.

1:26:32.555 --> 1:26:34.456
Okay.

1:26:34.456 --> 1:26:36.792
Thanks a lot. Bye-bye.

1:26:36.792 --> 1:26:38.427
Hey.
Hi.

1:26:38.427 --> 1:26:39.962
[punching keypad]

1:26:39.962 --> 1:26:43.399
Uh...

1:26:43.399 --> 1:26:47.836
I think I want to ask you
about the second floor,

1:26:47.836 --> 1:26:51.407
just to know
a little more about it.

1:26:51.407 --> 1:26:53.509
Well, it's for people
who've really lost it.

1:27:00.816 --> 1:27:03.519
What do they do, then?

1:27:03.519 --> 1:27:08.324
What happens after that?
After they've...lost it?

1:27:08.324 --> 1:27:10.426
You don't really
want to know.

1:27:10.426 --> 1:27:12.494
But, you know,
sometimes they get it back.

1:27:12.494 --> 1:27:15.431
They go into their room
for a year, they don't
know you from Adam,

1:27:15.431 --> 1:27:17.666
and then one day,
it's, "Oh, hi.
When are we going home?"

1:27:17.666 --> 1:27:20.269
I mean, all of a sudden,
they're back to normal.

1:27:20.269 --> 1:27:22.004
But it doesn't
last for long.

1:27:22.004 --> 1:27:23.806
You think,
"Oh, wow, back to normal,"

1:27:23.806 --> 1:27:25.608
and then they're gone again--

1:27:25.608 --> 1:27:27.543
[snaps fingers]
like so.

1:27:30.446 --> 1:27:33.549
I haven't even asked you
about yourself.

1:27:33.549 --> 1:27:34.950
You married?

1:27:34.950 --> 1:27:38.854
Well, technically,
yeah, I guess.

1:27:38.854 --> 1:27:40.923
Got three kids.

1:27:40.923 --> 1:27:43.525
Their dad lives
in Alberta, I think.

1:27:43.525 --> 1:27:45.728
He's making it rich, maybe.
I wouldn't know.

1:27:45.728 --> 1:27:48.364
Must be quite a struggle.

1:27:48.364 --> 1:27:52.301
It, uh...knocks the wind
out of you every now and then,

1:27:52.301 --> 1:27:55.571
but you just pick yourself
back up like everyone else.

1:27:57.439 --> 1:28:01.343
I suppose our lives
must seem easy to you.

1:28:01.343 --> 1:28:04.613
We got through life
without too much
going wrong.

1:28:04.613 --> 1:28:08.417
What we have to suffer
now, when we're old,

1:28:08.417 --> 1:28:10.019
hardly counts,
I suppose.

1:28:10.019 --> 1:28:12.588
That's
what you must think.

1:28:16.492 --> 1:28:18.861
Well, how would you
know what I think?

1:28:18.861 --> 1:28:20.763
To tell you the truth,
I'd rather be

1:28:20.763 --> 1:28:24.566
the one that stayed
than the one that left.

1:28:24.566 --> 1:28:26.902
I'll bet you weren't always
the doggedly devoted husband.

1:28:26.902 --> 1:28:29.571
Am I right?

1:28:29.571 --> 1:28:33.042
I mean, you said
that you wondered

1:28:33.042 --> 1:28:37.646
if maybe she was punishing
you for something?

1:28:37.646 --> 1:28:39.915
I'll bet you had something
pretty specific in mind,
didn't you?

1:28:42.918 --> 1:28:48.791
You know, you see a lot
of things in this job.

1:28:48.791 --> 1:28:51.593
You see the end of things
all day long.

1:28:51.593 --> 1:28:53.495
And in my experience,
at the end of things

1:28:53.495 --> 1:28:55.330
it's almost always
the men that think

1:28:55.330 --> 1:28:58.600
that not too much
went wrong.

1:28:58.600 --> 1:29:00.836
I wonder if your wife
feels the same way.

1:29:02.871 --> 1:29:04.740
I wonder that, too.

1:29:06.075 --> 1:29:08.510
I bet you do.

1:29:26.762 --> 1:29:31.467
[phone ringing]

1:29:31.467 --> 1:29:32.634
[answering machine beeps]

1:29:32.634 --> 1:29:34.436
[Marian]
Uh, hello, Grant.

1:29:34.436 --> 1:29:36.638
I hope I got
the right person.

1:29:36.638 --> 1:29:38.507
I just thought of something.

1:29:38.507 --> 1:29:40.676
There is a dance
here in town

1:29:40.676 --> 1:29:42.878
at the Legion
on Saturday night,

1:29:42.878 --> 1:29:44.646
and I am
on the supper committee,

1:29:44.646 --> 1:29:46.849
which means I can
bring a free guest.

1:29:46.849 --> 1:29:49.551
So I wondered
whether you would happen

1:29:49.551 --> 1:29:51.687
to be interested in that.

1:29:51.687 --> 1:29:54.089
Call me back
when you get a chance.

1:29:54.089 --> 1:29:57.826
555-3457.

1:29:57.826 --> 1:29:59.628
[click]

1:29:59.628 --> 1:30:01.530
[answering machine beeps]

1:30:01.530 --> 1:30:04.433
[Marian]
I just realizedI'd forgotten
to say who it was.

1:30:04.433 --> 1:30:05.667
[chuckles]

1:30:05.667 --> 1:30:08.804
Well, you probably recognize
the voice, the accent.

1:30:08.804 --> 1:30:10.472
It's Marian.

1:30:10.472 --> 1:30:12.775
I'm still not so used
to these machines,

1:30:12.775 --> 1:30:15.544
and I wanted to say
I realize you're not single

1:30:15.544 --> 1:30:17.646
and I don't mean it
that way.

1:30:17.646 --> 1:30:19.515
I'm not, either.

1:30:19.515 --> 1:30:22.651
But it doesn't hurt
to get out once in a while.

1:30:22.651 --> 1:30:24.920
Anyway,
now I've said all this,

1:30:24.920 --> 1:30:27.589
I really hope
it's you I'm talking to.

1:30:27.589 --> 1:30:29.691
It did sound like your voice.

1:30:29.691 --> 1:30:31.894
If you're interested,
you can call me.

1:30:31.894 --> 1:30:34.963
And if you are not,
you don't need to bother.

1:30:34.963 --> 1:30:39.568
I just thought you might
like the chance to get out.

1:30:39.568 --> 1:30:41.203
It's Marian speaking.

1:30:41.203 --> 1:30:43.138
[chuckling]

1:30:43.138 --> 1:30:46.608
I guess I already said that.

1:30:46.608 --> 1:30:49.745
Okay, then.
Good-bye.

1:30:53.749 --> 1:30:55.751
[Grant]
"The desires of the heart

1:30:55.751 --> 1:30:58.086
"are as crooked
as corkscrews.

1:30:58.086 --> 1:31:00.756
"Not to be born
is the best for man.

1:31:00.756 --> 1:31:04.193
"The second-best
is a formal order.

1:31:04.193 --> 1:31:08.630
The dance's pattern:
dance while you can."

1:31:13.836 --> 1:31:16.939
Fiona?

1:31:16.939 --> 1:31:19.942
Is there any way
to let this go...

1:31:19.942 --> 1:31:21.944
do you think?

1:31:26.181 --> 1:31:29.685
If I let it go,
it'll only hit me harder

1:31:29.685 --> 1:31:31.954
when I bump into it again.

1:31:37.226 --> 1:31:38.827
Okay.

1:31:43.699 --> 1:31:46.835
"Dance, dance,
for the figure is easy.

1:31:46.835 --> 1:31:50.639
The tune is catchy
and will not stop."

1:31:52.741 --> 1:31:54.076
[Grant]
"Dance till the stars

1:31:54.076 --> 1:31:56.078
"come down
from the rafters.

1:31:56.078 --> 1:31:59.615
Dance, dance, dance
till you drop."

1:31:59.615 --> 1:32:02.017
[phone ringing]

1:32:06.054 --> 1:32:07.890
[Marian]
Yes?

1:32:07.890 --> 1:32:10.058
Hello, Marian.

1:32:20.202 --> 1:32:21.770
So...

1:32:23.906 --> 1:32:25.574
There you are.

1:32:26.775 --> 1:32:28.777
Here I am.

1:32:31.780 --> 1:32:32.881
Thank you.

1:32:32.881 --> 1:32:35.984
â™ª [slow jazz]

1:32:59.107 --> 1:33:00.776
What are you thinking?

1:33:02.744 --> 1:33:04.780
Not an awful lot, really.

1:33:06.782 --> 1:33:08.917
Skiing.

1:33:12.187 --> 1:33:13.255
Downhill?

1:33:15.824 --> 1:33:16.892
Cross-country.

1:33:19.828 --> 1:33:23.332
I'm more a thrill-seeker,
I guess.

1:33:28.904 --> 1:33:30.072
What are you thinking?

1:33:31.907 --> 1:33:33.608
I'm thinking
you never know

1:33:33.608 --> 1:33:36.078
how things are going
to turn out.

1:33:38.914 --> 1:33:42.184
You almost know...

1:33:42.184 --> 1:33:46.121
but you can never
be quite sure.

1:34:22.257 --> 1:34:23.992
Mr. Andersson?

1:34:30.799 --> 1:34:32.801
Mr. Andersson?

1:34:32.801 --> 1:34:34.903
Now, as you know,
we're, uh,

1:34:34.903 --> 1:34:36.338
we're going to have to
think about moving

1:34:36.338 --> 1:34:40.042
Mrs. Andersson upstairs
fairly soon, I'm afraid.

1:34:40.042 --> 1:34:42.377
She hasn't been
out of that bed
for two weeks now, and--

1:34:42.377 --> 1:34:46.048
I'm quite aware
of your policies.

1:34:46.048 --> 1:34:48.183
I'm more than aware
of your bloody policies.

1:34:50.986 --> 1:34:53.922
[Frank]
Well, once again,
Nurse Kristy is taking me

1:34:53.922 --> 1:34:55.223
back to the second floor.

1:34:55.223 --> 1:34:57.159
The area to my right
are the elevators,

1:34:57.159 --> 1:34:59.194
and as we go on
down the hall,

1:34:59.194 --> 1:35:01.096
there's a man
with a broken heart,

1:35:01.096 --> 1:35:02.931
broken
in a thousand pieces.

1:35:02.931 --> 1:35:05.233
Well, we'll go
to Madeleine's office,
past the lunchroom.

1:35:05.233 --> 1:35:07.202
Hopefully,
they're serving right now.

1:35:07.202 --> 1:35:08.837
The cannelloni
was cold yesterday,

1:35:08.837 --> 1:35:10.205
but let's see
what it's doing today.

1:35:10.205 --> 1:35:12.207
Let's have-- I gotta have
some Cokes again.

1:35:12.207 --> 1:35:14.242
That's what I'm
going to do.

1:35:17.012 --> 1:35:21.883
Wouldn't it be better
if...

1:35:21.883 --> 1:35:24.853
when we go out again,

1:35:24.853 --> 1:35:27.456
to put Aubrey
back into Meadowlake?

1:35:27.456 --> 1:35:29.958
Just for a day?

1:35:29.958 --> 1:35:31.993
What do you think?

1:35:34.896 --> 1:35:39.868
I'm thinking
that sometimes you...

1:35:39.868 --> 1:35:44.406
just have to make
the decision to be happy.

1:35:46.975 --> 1:35:48.743
Just decide.

1:35:50.345 --> 1:35:53.982
Things aren't ever
what you hoped they'd be.

1:35:53.982 --> 1:35:55.884
Not ever, for anybody.

1:35:57.786 --> 1:35:59.187
The only thing
that separates

1:35:59.187 --> 1:36:01.456
one kind of person
from another

1:36:01.456 --> 1:36:05.460
is there are some
who stay angry about it

1:36:05.460 --> 1:36:09.097
and there
are some who...

1:36:09.097 --> 1:36:11.466
accept
what comes their way.

1:36:13.101 --> 1:36:14.503
And which kind
of person are you?

1:36:16.037 --> 1:36:19.474
I was pretty mad
about it.

1:36:19.474 --> 1:36:22.544
But now...

1:36:22.544 --> 1:36:27.382
looking at what
came my way...

1:36:32.087 --> 1:36:35.023
I think I could be
the other kind of person.

1:36:38.026 --> 1:36:40.495
Quite the philosopher,
huh?

1:36:43.965 --> 1:36:45.467
Look, why don't you
pull over here?

1:36:45.467 --> 1:36:49.871
Just...
pull over, could you?

1:37:00.882 --> 1:37:03.151
Ahem.

1:37:05.554 --> 1:37:07.222
I know what you're doing.

1:37:09.024 --> 1:37:12.227
It would be easier for me

1:37:12.227 --> 1:37:14.095
if you could pretend
a little.

1:37:15.564 --> 1:37:17.899
Do you think
you could do that?

1:37:32.914 --> 1:37:35.550
Now, what were
we talking about?

1:38:21.162 --> 1:38:22.998
She was the only one
in her family

1:38:22.998 --> 1:38:24.199
who bothered to learn
sign language.

1:38:25.667 --> 1:38:30.238
Now she can't remember how,
or maybe even who she is.

1:38:30.238 --> 1:38:31.539
Her daughter?

1:38:31.539 --> 1:38:33.308
Yeah.

1:38:33.308 --> 1:38:36.211
It's left her
pretty stranded.

1:38:36.211 --> 1:38:38.246
Marooned.

1:38:40.282 --> 1:38:42.150
You know,
I thought of you
the other day.

1:38:42.150 --> 1:38:44.052
You know that billboard
out in front

1:38:44.052 --> 1:38:45.320
of the United Church
in Bradford,

1:38:45.320 --> 1:38:48.957
they post all that
biblical-type stuff?

1:38:48.957 --> 1:38:52.260
The other day, it said,

1:38:52.260 --> 1:38:53.662
"It's never too late

1:38:53.662 --> 1:38:55.297
to become what you
might have been."

1:38:57.565 --> 1:39:01.369
Doesn't sound
all that biblical.

1:39:01.369 --> 1:39:03.972
Well, maybe they're
getting creative on us.

1:39:23.425 --> 1:39:25.126
